let _markdown = "\n\n# Hi-C Python API\n\nComplete Python API for analyzing Hi-C data for genome-wide chromatin architecture studies.\n\n## Overview\n\nHi-C captures all chromatin interactions genome-wide without protein-specific enrichment. The Chr3D Hi-C pipeline generates contact matrices at multiple resolutions using pairtools and cooler.\n\n**Note**: Hi-C mode does **not** include peak calling or loop calling (no protein enrichment). Use external tools like HiCCUPS, Mustache, or cooltools for downstream analysis.\n\n## Complete Pipeline Example\n\n```python\nimport sys\nsys.path.insert(0, '/path/to/Chr3D/src')\n\nfrom chr3d.bulk_hic import HiCPipeline\n\n# Configuration\nfastq_r1 = \"/data/HiC_sample_R1.fastq.gz\"\nfastq_r2 = \"/data/HiC_sample_R2.fastq.gz\"\ngenome_index = \"/ref/hg38.fa\"\nchrom_sizes = \"/ref/hg38.chrom.sizes\"\noutput_dir = \"/output/hic_analysis\"\n\n# Initialize pipeline\nhic_pipeline = HiCPipeline(\n    genome_index=genome_index,\n    chrom_sizes=chrom_sizes,\n    threads=8,\n    assembly='hg38',\n    min_mapq=30,\n    min_distance=1000,\n    resolutions=[1000, 5000, 10000, 25000, 50000, 100000]\n)\n\n# Run complete pipeline\nstats = hic_pipeline.run(\n    fastq1=fastq_r1,\n    fastq2=fastq_r2,\n    output_dir=output_dir,\n    sample_id='HiC_experiment',\n    cleanup=True  # Remove intermediate files\n)\n\n# Print results\nprint(f\"Total pairs: {stats.get('total_pairs', 'N/A'):,}\")\nprint(f\"Cis pairs: {stats.get('cis_pairs', 'N/A'):,}\")\nprint(f\"Trans pairs: {stats.get('trans_pairs', 'N/A'):,}\")\nprint(f\"Output: {output_dir}/HiC_experiment.mcool\")\n```\n\n## Module Reference\n\n### HiCPipeline\n\nComplete Hi-C processing pipeline using pairtools and cooler.\n\n```python\nfrom chr3d.bulk_hic import HiCPipeline\n\npipeline = HiCPipeline(\n    genome_index: str,              # BWA-indexed genome FASTA\n    chrom_sizes: str,               # Chromosome sizes file\n    threads: int = 8,               # Number of threads\n    assembly: str = 'hg38',         # Genome assembly name\n    min_mapq: int = 30,             # Minimum mapping quality\n    min_distance: int = 1000,       # Minimum distance for valid pairs\n    resolutions: List[int] = [1000, 5000, 10000]  # Matrix resolutions\n)\n```\n\n#### run()\n\nRun the complete Hi-C pipeline.\n\n```python\nstats = pipeline.run(\n    fastq1: str,                    # Input R1 FASTQ\n    fastq2: str,                    # Input R2 FASTQ\n    output_dir: str,                # Output directory\n    sample_id: str = 'sample',      # Sample identifier\n    cleanup: bool = True            # Remove intermediate files\n) -> Dict\n```\n\n**Returns:**\n\n```python\n{\n    'total_pairs': int,\n    'mapped_pairs': int,\n    'unique_pairs': int,\n    'cis_pairs': int,\n    'trans_pairs': int,\n    'cis_ratio': float,\n    'duplicate_rate': float,\n    'output_mcool': str\n}\n```\n\n## Pipeline Steps\n\nThe `HiCPipeline.run()` method executes these steps:\n\n### Step 1: BWA-MEM Alignment\n\nMaps paired-end reads to reference genome.\n\n```python\n# Internal: Uses subprocess to run BWA-MEM\nbwa mem -SP5M -t {threads} {genome_index} {fastq1} {fastq2}\n```\n\n### Step 2: Pairtools Parse\n\nConverts aligned BAM to pairs format.\n\n```python\n# Internal: pairtools parse\npairtools parse --min-mapq {min_mapq} \\\n    --walks-policy 5unique \\\n    --max-inter-align-gap 30 \\\n    --chroms-path {chrom_sizes} \\\n    {input_bam}\n```\n\n### Step 3: Pairtools Sort\n\nSorts pairs by genomic coordinates.\n\n```python\n# Internal: pairtools sort\npairtools sort --nproc {threads} {input_pairs}\n```\n\n### Step 4: Pairtools Dedup\n\nRemoves PCR duplicates.\n\n```python\n# Internal: pairtools dedup\npairtools dedup --max-mismatch 3 {input_pairs}\n```\n\n### Step 5: Pairtools Select\n\nFilters for valid cis pairs.\n\n```python\n# Internal: pairtools select\npairtools select '(pair_type == \"UU\") and (chrom1 == chrom2) and (abs(pos1 - pos2) >= {min_distance})'\n```\n\n### Step 6: Cooler Cload\n\nCreates contact matrix from pairs.\n\n```python\n# Internal: cooler cload pairs\ncooler cload pairs -c1 2 -p1 3 -c2 4 -p2 5 \\\n    {chrom_sizes}:{resolution} \\\n    {input_pairs} \\\n    {output_cool}\n```\n\n### Step 7: Cooler Zoomify\n\nCreates multi-resolution .mcool file.\n\n```python\n# Internal: cooler zoomify\ncooler zoomify --resolutions {resolutions} {input_cool}\n```\n\n## Output Files\n\n```\noutput_dir/\n├── aligned/\n│   └── sample.bam\n├── pairs/\n│   ├── sample.pairs.gz\n│   ├── sample.sorted.pairs.gz\n│   ├── sample.dedup.pairs.gz\n│   └── sample.filtered.pairs.gz\n├── matrices/\n│   └── sample.mcool\n├── processed/\n│   └── sample.valid_pairs.txt\n└── qc/\n    ├── sample_pairs.stats\n    ├── sample_dedup.stats\n    └── sample_summary.txt\n```\n\n## Working with Output Files\n\n### Loading .mcool Files\n\n```python\nimport cooler\n\n# Load specific resolution\nclr = cooler.Cooler(\"sample.mcool::resolutions/10000\")\n\n# Get matrix for region\nmatrix = clr.matrix(balance=False).fetch(\"chr1:1000000-2000000\")\n\n# Get balanced (normalized) matrix\nmatrix_balanced = clr.matrix(balance=True).fetch(\"chr1:1000000-2000000\")\n\n# Get bins\nbins = clr.bins()[:]\n\n# Get chromosome info\nchroms = clr.chromsizes\n```\n\n### Normalization with Cooler\n\n```python\nimport cooler\n\n# Load cooler\nclr = cooler.Cooler(\"sample.mcool::resolutions/10000\")\n\n# ICE normalization (iterative correction)\ncooler.balance_cooler(clr, store=True)\n\n# Access balanced weights\nweights = clr.bins()['weight'][:]\n```\n\n## Downstream Analysis\n\n### TAD Calling with Cooltools\n\n```python\nimport cooltools\nimport cooler\n\nclr = cooler.Cooler(\"sample.mcool::resolutions/10000\")\n\n# Calculate insulation score\ninsulation = cooltools.insulation(clr, window_bp=[100000, 200000])\n\n# Find TAD boundaries\nboundaries = cooltools.find_boundaries(insulation)\n```\n\n### Compartment Analysis\n\n```python\nimport cooltools\n\nclr = cooler.Cooler(\"sample.mcool::resolutions/100000\")\n\n# Calculate eigenvectors for compartments\neigs = cooltools.eigs_cis(clr, n_eigs=3)\n\n# First eigenvector corresponds to A/B compartments\ncompartments = eigs[0]\n```\n\n### Loop Calling with HiCCUPS\n\n```bash\n# Using Juicer tools (external)\njava -jar juicer_tools.jar hiccups \\\n    sample.hic \\\n    loops_output\n```\n\n### Visualization\n\n```python\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nimport cooler\n\nclr = cooler.Cooler(\"sample.mcool::resolutions/10000\")\n\n# Get matrix\nmatrix = clr.matrix(balance=True).fetch(\"chr1:50000000-60000000\")\n\n# Plot\nplt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))\nplt.imshow(matrix, cmap='YlOrRd', vmax=0.01)\nplt.colorbar(label='Normalized contacts')\nplt.title('Hi-C Contact Matrix')\nplt.savefig('hic_matrix.png', dpi=150)\n```\n\n## QC Statistics\n\nThe pipeline generates QC statistics in `qc/sample_pairs.stats`:\n\n| Metric            | Description                |\n| ----------------- | -------------------------- |\n| total             | Total read pairs           |\n| total\\_mapped     | Successfully mapped pairs  |\n| total\\_dups       | Duplicate pairs            |\n| total\\_nodups     | Unique pairs               |\n| cis               | Same-chromosome pairs      |\n| trans             | Different-chromosome pairs |\n| cis\\_1kb+         | Cis pairs >1kb apart       |\n| cis\\_10kb+        | Cis pairs >10kb apart      |\n| summary/frac\\_cis | Fraction of cis pairs      |\n\n## Quality Metrics\n\n**Good Hi-C Data:**\n\n| Metric         | Good  | Acceptable | Poor  |\n| -------------- | ----- | ---------- | ----- |\n| Mapping rate   | >90%  | 70-90%     | \\<70% |\n| Cis ratio      | >60%  | 40-60%     | \\<40% |\n| Cis >10kb      | >40%  | 20-40%     | \\<20% |\n| Duplicate rate | \\<20% | 20-40%     | >40%  |\n\n## Resolution Guidelines\n\n| Resolution | Use Case          | Memory   |\n| ---------- | ----------------- | -------- |\n| 1kb        | Fine-scale loops  | High     |\n| 5kb        | Loop detection    | Medium   |\n| 10kb       | TAD calling       | Medium   |\n| 25kb       | Compartments      | Low      |\n| 50kb       | Overview          | Low      |\n| 100kb      | Whole-genome view | Very Low |\n\n## Hi-C vs HiChIP vs ChIA-PET\n\n| Feature        | Hi-C           | HiChIP           | ChIA-PET         |\n| -------------- | -------------- | ---------------- | ---------------- |\n| Enrichment     | None           | ChIP             | ChIP             |\n| Interactions   | All            | Protein-specific | Protein-specific |\n| Resolution     | Genome-wide    | Focused          | Focused          |\n| Input cells    | 1-10M          | 1M               | 100M             |\n| Loop calling   | External tools | Built-in         | Built-in         |\n| Peak calling   | No             | Yes              | Yes              |\n| Contact matrix | Yes (.mcool)   | No               | No               |\n\n## Generating Chromosome Sizes\n\n```python\n# Using pysam\nimport pysam\n\nfasta = pysam.FastaFile(\"/ref/hg38.fa\")\nwith open(\"/ref/hg38.chrom.sizes\", \"w\") as f:\n    for chrom in fasta.references:\n        f.write(f\"{chrom}\\t{fasta.get_reference_length(chrom)}\\n\")\n```\n\nOr using samtools:\n\n```bash\nsamtools faidx /ref/hg38.fa\ncut -f1,2 /ref/hg38.fa.fai > /ref/hg38.chrom.sizes\n```\n\n## Tips\n\n1. **Sequencing Depth**: Aim for >500M read pairs for 1kb resolution\n2. **Memory**: High resolutions require significant RAM (>64GB for 1kb)\n3. **Storage**: .mcool files can be large (10-100GB)\n4. **Normalization**: Always use balanced matrices for analysis\n5. **Multiple Resolutions**: Generate multiple for different analyses\n";
